claim.claim-text:
5. An optical disk apparatus for recording information by forming marks and spaces on an optical disk, comprising:
a laser diode for irradiating laser beam on said optical disk;
a laser diode driver including a high-frequency current output circuit for outputting a high frequency current and a direct-current output circuit for outputting a direct current, said laser diode driver driving said laser diode;
a front monitor for detecting an output power of said laser diode;
a first current/voltage conversion circuit for converting an output current from said front monitor into a voltage;
a disk-reflected light detecting element for detecting reflected light from said optical disk;
a second current/voltage conversion circuit for converting an output current from said disk-reflected light detecting element into a voltage;
a controller for controlling said laser diode driver; and
a flexible cable for connecting said laser diode driver with said controller,
wherein said controller controls such that said laser diode driver supplies a high-frequency-superimposing drive current to said laser diode during a space-forming time period, and controls such that said supply is stopped prior to a predetermined duration for a timing of changing from said space-forming-time period to an adjacent mark-forming time period, and
wherein the predetermined duration is higher than zero.

6. An optical disk apparatus for recording information by forming marks and spaces on an optical disk, comprising:
a laser diode for irradiating laser beam on said optical disk;
a laser diode driver including a high-frequency current output circuit for outputting a high frequency current and a direct-current output circuit for outputting a direct current, said laser diode driver driving said laser diode;
a front monitor for detecting an output power of said laser diode;
a first current/voltage conversion circuit for converting an output current from said front monitor into a voltage;
a disk-reflected light detecting element for detecting reflected light from said optical disk;
a second current/voltage conversion circuit for converting an output current from said disk-reflected light detecting element into a voltage;
a controller for controlling said laser diode driver; and
a flexible cable for connecting said laser diode driving unit with said control unit,
wherein said controller controls such that said laser diode driver supplies a high-frequency-superimposing drive current to said laser diode during a space-forming time period, and controls such that said supply is started subsequent to a predetermined duration for a timing of changing from said mark-forming-time period to an adjacent space-forming time period, and
wherein the predetermined duration is higher than zero.
